<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUN 92 / The Lisbon Summit: Opting-out gains respectability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of the Maastricht Treaty may be in doubt. But for precisely that
reason, a Maastricht syndrome is already shaping the way the European
Community does business.
There is a general and over-arching debate about 'subsidiarity' - trying to
separate what the EC should be responsible for and what member states should
keep. The working time directive is the prime example of how uncertainty
over the EC's future is already bending legislation plans, and introducing
the sort of 'opt-outs' pioneered at December's Maastricht summit.
Late Wednesday night this controversial draft law came within a whisker of
being the first practical example of how the EC moves forward while its
members go at different speeds, via routes different enough to obscure the
actual direction. What was agreed exemplified the increasingly touted
'Europe a la carte,' or 'variable geometry,' through which countries pick
and choose the policies they feel comfortable with.
Alone among its partners, the UK had steadfastly opposed this EC proposal to
put a uniform 48-hour limit on the working week.
Nevertheless, after intensive negotiations between the UK, France and
Germany, designed to accommodate the different political needs of these
three largest member states, the 'British problem' was solved. Only an
ostensibly technical disagreement between the French and Germans postponed
full consensus.
The solution shows how the new system works. Britain will be able to
postpone the 48-hour week for initially ten years, after when there will be
an EC 'review' which legally, at least, does not prejudice the outcome.
This is as far away as one can get from a 'derogation', or time limited
exemption, towards an 'opt-out', without actually arriving. 'A masterpiece
of draftsmanship,' said one senior Irish diplomat with more than a hint of a
smile.
It is also an instance of the multi-speed Europe foreshadowed at Maastricht,
mainly through the UK's opt-out there from its partners' plans to develop EC
social policy.
The need for a show of EC unity, if not consensus, on the eve of today's
Lisbon summit of Community leaders and following the Danish rejection of
Maastricht, drove the 11th-hour negotiations on the directive. For the UK,
equally important was the preservation of the government's intention of
operating in "the heart of Europe' - and securing its strengthening alliance
with Germany.
When push came to shove, however, it was Germany which three times
interceded to ensure the UK would not be outvoted, and France which picked
up the ball to negotiate the final compromise with Britain.
Both France and Germany were anxious to protect Britain's Tory government
from its Euro-sceptic supporters, who see labour market deregulation as a
Thatcherite shibboleth.
Yet France, after pulling on board the UK, then decided to hold up final
agreement. Paris, facing a referendum on Maastricht, fears that a directive
which appears to dilute social provisions could invite attack from the
mainly Communist left, which is hostile to the treaty, according to a senior
EC official.
Denmark's rejection of Maastricht has led to more than usually acidulous
devotion to national concerns in EC decision-making. For the moment this
mostly favours the big countries on whom the treaty's future depends.
But, as the sort of legal arabesques, procedural fudges, and vigorously
prosecuted special pleading evidenced in the working-time directive become
more acceptable, Europe a la carte collects credentials.
This is just the sort of loosening wanted by the UK, which takes over the EC
presidency next week.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
