<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Jupiter Tyndall outlines reorganisation of
Pacific
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUPITER Tyndall Merlin, the fund manager for Pacific Horizon Investment
Trust, yesterday announced plans to reorganise the trust's capital
structure.
Jupiter Tyndall amassed a stake of 25.1 per cent of Pacific Horizons's
warrants, which it used to block offers from Martin Currie Pacific
investment trust, the latest of which was last week allowed to lapse.
The reorganisation would involve issuing zero coupon convertible unsecured
loan stock (Culs) in place of nine tenths of the existing ordinary share
capital.
A subsidiary of Pacific Horizon would then be set up which could tender for
up to 60 per cent of the loan stock issued at a price equivalent to 90 per
cent of the adjusted net asset value per share of the company.
Warrant terms would also be amended so that one warrant upon exercise, could
be exchanged for one ordinary share and nine zero Culs.
This structure would narrow the discount between Pacific Horizon's share
price and its net asset value per share. The shares added 1p to 23p
yesterday, the warrants 1p to 10p.
Jupiter Tyndall intends to requisition an extraordinary general meeting of
Pacific Horizon to consider the reconstruction plans. It will also seek to
appoint new directors and seek the resignations of certain existing
directors.
The board had unanimously recommended the Martin Currie offer in a statement
made at the beginning of this month, which also expressed concern at the
effect Jupiter Tyndall's management functions could have on its
independence.
