<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / Toronto judge adjourns O&amp;Y hearing on costs payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A TORONTO judge last night adjourned until Monday a hearing on the issue of
how Olympia &amp; York Developments, the Reichmann family company under Canadian
bankruptcy court protection, will obtain an estimated CDollars 40m (Pounds
18m) needed to pay its overhead and restructuring costs over the next few
months.
The adjournment came several hours after O&amp;Y proposed to its creditors a
plan to sell an assortment of minor assets that carry a book value of
CDollars 70m and are held by the Canadian parent company and it
subsidiaries.
The proposal was aimed at countering creditors' objections to paying most of
O&amp;Y's costs without receiving any compensation. Lawyers for a number of
secured and unsecured creditors objected to the O&amp;Y proposal, with the
former arguing against putting up any fresh money and the latter saying the
proposal discriminates against them.
In the US, meanwhile, it emerged that O&amp;Y is hoping to raise at least
Dollars 100m (Pounds 54m) by selling a minority shareholding in its main US
property subsidiary to one or more investors.
The possible sale of such an equity stake would be part of a complex US
restructuring plan that began taking shape this week with the hiring by O&amp;Y
of Mr Patrick Ahern, a former Lehman Brothers partner who has been named as
chief restructuring officer in New York.
O&amp;Y's US subsidiary is the only significant part of the Reichmann empire
that has not been placed in administration or filed for bankruptcy
protection.
Mr Ahern was described by an O&amp;Y adviser yesterday as the US counterpart to
Mr Steve Miller, the chief O&amp;Y bank negotiator.
Mr Ahern will be working on the restructuring plan with US partners from
Price Waterhouse, the long-time auditor of O&amp;Y, according to the O&amp;Y
adviser.
The O&amp;Y adviser said discussions were already under way with prospective
investors who might buy a stake in the Canadian group's US company - Olympia
&amp; York Companies (USA). He declined to name the possible investors.
The Dollars 100m-plus will be needed by O&amp;Y by next year, to finance needed
repairs, maintenance and tenant improvements on US properties. The talks
with prospective equity partners are being handled by Mr John Zucotti, head
of O&amp;Y's US operations.
In a related development, O&amp;Y said that it had raised Dollars 32.5m as a
result of the sale of an 11 per cent shareholding in Hyperion Partners, an
investment fund.
This cash could help O&amp;Y to avert the need to file in the near term for
protection from creditors under US bankruptcy law.
Mr Nigel Hamilton, a partner of Ernst &amp; Young, administrator to Canary
Wharf, held a 'routine' meeting with representatives of the scheme's 12 main
lenders in Toronto yesterday.
</TEXT>
