<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Anger greets Labour decision on
selection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CHORUS of angry criticism followed a 13-8 vote by the Labour's national
executive committee yesterday to postpone the introduction of a one-member,
one-vote selection system for MPs.
The NEC reversed an earlier decision to put the change to the party's
conference and decided instead to include it in a general review of union
links. The NEC thus in effect shelved a nine-year campaign by Mr Neil
Kinnock, the party's outgoing leader, to exclude unions from the process.
Critics of the decision said it had served only to highlight the timidity of
the party when faced with the power of union bosses.
Several singled out Mr John Edmonds, leader of the GMB general union, as the
main figure behind the reversal.
Mr George Howarth, MP for Knowsley North, commented ironically that it only
remained for Mr Edmonds to be officially confirmed as party leader. Another
high ranking party official described Mr Edmonds' behind-the-scenes
activities as akin to 'a rogue elephant' on the loose.
Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU general union and an opponent
of deep reforms, also let his deep displeasure with the decision be known
yesterday.
He said he had not been consulted on his inclusion in the review committee
and that he may not participate.
Defending the vote, Mr Larry Whitty, Labour's general secretary, insisted
that by including the plan in the review the NEC was avoiding making
'piecemeal' changes.
He added that while NEC backing for the change on selection procedures was
not in doubt, a full-scale 'divorce' between the party and the unions was
also not on the cards.
Other NEC members made clear that the move was taken to avoid embarrassing
Mr John Smith, now certain to be elected leader on July 18.
Amid growing union resentment at the public criticism of their influence,
the proposal would almost certainly have been voted down had it gone to
conference.
That confrontation may, nonetheless, take place after the reform-minded AEEU
engineering and electrical union yesterday tabled a conference motion
backing a one-member, one-vote selection process.
In an effort to calm tempers, Mr Kinnock used his last NEC meeting as party
leader to argue the case for his proposal. But he then voted to put the
issue to the review 'in the interests of party unity'.
Others were not so easily mollified. Opponents pointed out that the NEC
motion proposing that MP selection be part of the general review was moved
by Mr Robin Cook, campaign manager for the shadow chancellor, who in turn
was a GMB-sponsored MP.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-846</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFYA4AE7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920625
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tory unease over upturn intensifies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, ALISON SMITH and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GROWING DISQUIET among Tory MPs about the weakness of the recovery surfaced
yesterday in a public demand that Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, should
extend the stamp duty 'holiday' for many house purchases.
The call - in a Commons motion signed by 26 Tories - coincides with
widespread acknowledgement among cabinet ministers that the party's election
victory has failed to bring the promised revival.
Mr Lamont's colleagues now expect the Treasury to revise down from 1 per
cent to zero its forecast of output growth this year. But they denied that
the chancellor faced cabinet pressure to risk sterling's stability in the
exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System by forcing the pace
on interest-rate cuts.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, is understood to be keen for a small
reduction in rates. But he is said to back the chancellor's view that any
such move must be dictated by the financial markets rather than by political
pressures.
Mr Lamont last week underlined the government's commitment to sterling's ERM
parity, telling Conservative MPs that a relaxation of the government's
anti-inflation stance would wreck the medium-term prospects for the economy.
The unease among Tory backbenchers about the slow pace of recovery falls
significantly short of a rebellion, but it is reinforced by a separate
attack on sterling's participation in the ERM.
Conservative opponents of the Maastricht accord have seized on the
stubbornness of the recession to strengthen their demands for a sharp cut in
interest rates regardless of the impact on sterling.
Yesterday's Commons motion was seen as a broader warning from the
government's supporters of their impatience at the depth of the recession.
It was signed by MPs representing a broad spectrum of opinion in the party
Mr Lamont has made it clear he intends to stick to his plans to reimpose
stamp duty on all house purchases. The temporary moratorium - until
mid-August - of stamp duty on house sales below Pounds 250,000 was announced
last December to stimulate the housing market.
But the message from many Tories is that the measure has so far failed to
provide any significant boost to the construction industry. Sir Malcolm
Thornton, the Crosby MP who organised the motion, said he would be seeking a
statement of intent from Mr Lamont before the Commons rises next month for
the summer.
There were signs at Westminster last night that Labour might seek to
capitalise on the motion by incorporating an extension of the stamp-duty
holiday in an amendment to the finance bill. That would leave the government
facing a possible defeat as its Commons majority falls short of the 26
signatures on the motion.
A handful of Tory backbenchers whose local councils have had their budgets
disrupted through the 'capping' of their poll tax or community charge
refused to support the government in the Commons last night, Ivor Owen
writes.
Their gesture made little impact, however, as the government secured a
majority of 58 (312-254) approving the order endorsing capping.
Mr Michael Shersby, MP for Uxbridge, criticised the rigid formula applied by
the Department of Education.
This, he said, had resulted in his local education authority being deprived
of Pounds 1m because 15 per cent of the schools in the borough had opted out
of its control by securing grant maintained status.
</TEXT>
