Mr Hurd said the European Community had an opportunity to embody into its
workings the principle of decisions being made at the lowest appropriate
level.
Several of the 50 Tories who attended the meeting of the backbench Europe
and foreign affairs committee, remained unconvinced that a greater emphasis
on 'subsidiarity' would prevent an increase in European centralisation. 'The
unpersuadables were out in force,' said one MP.
