The conservative party is to take a first step towards widening public
information on its finances.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy firm, is to be consulted on the
feasibility of publishing a similar amount of information as in companies'
annual reports. That could include, for the first time, detailed figures on
debts.
Mr Tim Smith, the Tory vice-chairman with responsibility for party finances,
hopes he may be able to make the changes before 1992-93 accounts next
summer. However, he has ruled out publishing a breakdown of donations.
