<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / More freedom urged for aid body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government-controlled Commonwealth Development Corporation should be
given greater financial freedom to support projects in the developing world,
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission said yesterday.
Endorsing the role of the development corporation, which provides loans and
equity capital for projects in 68 developing countries, the commission said
the corporation's funds should be less vulnerable to Treasury cuts, and it
'should be free to expand its activities by financing more projects and
investing at a greater rate'.
The commission examined the corporation's role in Britain's aid policy and
the way it is managed. It said the corporation provided a very effective
form of aid and was highly regarded in the developing countries. Its
strengths 'fit well with the trend of international thinking on development
assistance', placing appropriate emphasis on the private sector as an
vehicle for growth in the developing countries.
The commission was asked in November last year to investigate whether the
corporation could improve its efficiency and reduce costs. Its report said
there were no significant savings to be made - although its assessment was
coloured by the development corporation's 'unique and ambiguous character'.
The report added that efficiency could be improved, but largely by loosening
government control. The corporation's contribution to aid policy was
'particularly important'.
The report identified areas for possible improvement:
The corporation should have its own equity capital. The lack of it 'gives
the impression that it is only an extension of government'. This should be
in the form of public dividend capital, and should be provided either as new
money, or by converting the corporation's outstanding borrowings.
The corporation's ambiguous 'quasi-commercial' status should be resolved by
dividing it into two parts - one to operate entirely commercially in
prosperous developing countries, and the other to be 'aimed at the poorest
countries'.
The organisation's funds should be set as a given percentage of the UK aid
programme. At present if it boosts its income the government can cut its
funding, reducing the incentive for it to expand its activities.
The report reached no conclusion on whether the development corporation
should be privatised, partly because of fears that this might compromise its
development role, but called for further consideration of this by ministers.
Efficiency and Costs and the Service Provided by the Commonwealth
Development Corporation. HMSO. Pounds 15.80
</TEXT>
