<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / Queen mother with tusk disappoints: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 'staff god' from Rarotonga in the Cook Islands, submitted for
identification at Sotheby's front counter, sold for Pounds 220,000 at the
auction house yesterday.
The staff is presumed to have been carved before 1820, when missionaries
destroyed the local religion. It has a stylised human head and other figures
and was probably treated as an object of worship. The price was at the lower
end of the estimate. Sotheby's tribal art sale was much concerned with queen
mothers, important figures in the culture of what is now Nigeria. The two
main lots failed to sell.
A 14 1/2 in-high Benin brass memorial head of an Oba (or queen mother), out
of which extended a carved ivory tusk more than 5ft long, was bought in at
Pounds 85,000. The tusk was created around 1814 as a memorial to Ose by her
son, the king Obanosa, even though he had had her executed after she plotted
against him. A Benin bronze head of an Oba, dated around 1600, was also
unsold at Pounds 90,000.
At Christie's an affectionate letter written by Mozart to his wife Constanze
in 1789, once owned by the soprano Jenny Lind, sold for Pounds 60,500. The
price was above estimate: letters from Mozart to his wife rarely appear at
auction.
The top price in a musical manuscript sale was the Pounds 297,000 paid for
Schubert's working manuscript of his quartet in B flat major written for his
family to perform in 1814 when he was 17.
Chopin's autograph manuscript of his Grande Valse Brillante was on target at
Pounds 60,500, while Beethoven's first jottings for his overture The
Consecration of the House made Pounds 33,000. The 50 lots brought in Pounds
612,000 and marked Christie's most successful sale in this market for many
years.
</TEXT>
