FT  25 JUN 92 / Lloyd's losses top 2bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOSSES for the 1989 underwriting account increased to Pounds 2.06bn compared
with Pounds 510m in 1988, according to preliminary unaudited figures
released yesterday by Lloyd's, Richard Lapper writes.
Underwriting losses in 1989 were Pounds 1.37bn, while Names' personal
expenses amounted to Pounds 292m. An extra Pounds 398m was earmarked to
strengthen reserves for claims expected to emerge on business underwritten
in earlier years.
Syndicates in the non-marine and marine market were worst hit with losses
climbing to Pounds 1.76bn (Pounds 1.14bn) and Pounds 1.32bn (Pounds 821m)
respectively. Syndicates in the aviation and motor markets made profits of
Pounds 281m (Pounds 16m) and Pounds 597m (Pounds 52m) respectively.
The worst losses were heavily concentrated among a minority of syndicates
specialising in catastrophe reinsurance business. Five syndicates (255, 290,
298, 540 and 847) accounted for 34 per cent of the overall loss and two
agencies accounted for 37 per cent of the loss  - Gooda Walker with 25 per
cent and Feltrim with 12 per cent.
Lloyd's also gave details on the strength of its asset base last year. The
premium trust funds - into which insurance premiums are paid - rose from
Pounds 9.80bn to Pounds 12.25bn.
</TEXT>
