<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / MP says DTI ignored Maxwell warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN MP campaigning for the Maxwell pensioners has accused the Department of
Trade and Industry of ignoring warnings from the Investment Management
Regulatory Organisation (Imro) that it felt unable to carry out its duties
adequately.
Mr Richard Page, the Tory co-chairman of the cross-party group of 100 MPs
who have taken up the pensioners' cause, has written to Mr William Reid, the
parliamentary ombudsman. Mr Page argues that the DTI failed to respond to
warnings from Imro about the difficulties of combining the Financial
Services Act with trust law; and this failure contributed to the inadequacy
of protection for Maxwell pensioners.
MPs campaigning on behalf of the pensioners believe an investigation by the
ombudsman would be critical to establishing the extent of government
responsibility. Mr Page's letter says Imro expressed concern to the DTI as
early as 1987 about the difficulties of combining the act and trust law, but
that the DTI took no action. In September 1990, he says, Imro submitted to
the DTI a paper on the same subject which the department also disregarded.
The letter is in response to a statement by Mr Reid earlier this month that
he might be able to consider any evidence that the DTI had ignored
representations about the adequacy of regulations. Making clear the limits
of his jurisdiction, Mr Reid had said he could not entertain complaints
against the Securities and Investments Board or Imro.
Although Mr Reid also said any evidence that the DTI's licensing of London &amp;
Bishopsgate International Investment Management in 1988 led to losses by the
pensioners could be considered, Mr Page's letter does not refer to this.
Downing Street said earlier this week it was satisfied that the appropriate
checks were made when the licence was granted: Robert Maxwell did not become
a director of LBI until some weeks after it had received its original
licence.
Although the government disputed the findings, the 1989 report of Sir
Anthony Barrowclough, then parliamentary ombudsman, led to aid for 18,000
investors who lost money when Barlow Clowes collapsed. Sir Anthony noted
'the lack of a sufficiently rigorous and inquiring approach' in the
government and the inadequacy of regulatory machinery before April 1988 when
the act was introduced.
Letters, Page 19
