<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / UK wins EC working hours deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK last night reached a compromise with its EC partners on European
Community limits to working time which it had previously said it could never
accept.
But final agreement was held up by a Franco-German dispute over the number
of months during which the proposed 48-hour limit on the working week should
be averaged.
The compromise came at a meeting in Luxembourg of ministers responsible for
working conditions.
Under the compromise, Britain secured a partial opt-out on introducing the
48-hour maximum working week. It would get a 10-year grace period, while the
other 11 EC member states must introduce the measure within three years.
In Britain's case, the EC council of ministers would 'review' the situation
after its additional seven-year grace period, leaving open the question of
whether the UK adopts it even at that stage.
But Britain would for the first time have to provide legal protection for
workers who do not want to work more than 48 hours and to bring in
legislation on mandatory time off.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, UK employment secretary, said: 'In a word, we've won.
I had to make on concessions whatsoever.'
She said that legislation the UK would have to enact to conform with the
planned EC directive was still 'a long way off' and that Britain had
'slashed the costs' of introducing it.
Despite her claim of victory, Mrs Shepard added: 'We have not ruled out. . .
the possibility of legal challenge' to the directive. The UK insists the EC
measure should not have been tabled under health and safety regulations,
which allow majority voting and override national vetoes.
Mr Tony Blair, the Labour opposition's employment spokesman, said 'the
British government has been forced to concede much on the working-time
directive that will benefit British employees'.
Mr Norman Willis, TUC general secretary hailed 'a major step forward for the
UK and a major climbdown by the government'.
The compromise followed negotiations on Tuesday between Mrs Shephard and Ms
Martine Aubry, the French labour minister.
Although a deal was not finalised, this did not overshadow member states'
efforts to demonstrate unity in the face of current uncertainty over the
Maastricht treaty on the eve of tomorrow's EC summit in Lisbon.
Final passage of the EC directive will now be stewarded by the UK presidency
of the Community, which begins next week. Ms Vasso Papandreou, the EC social
affairs commissioner, said how the UK handled the issue 'will be a test of
the British presidency and whether it acts impartially'.
Germans urge rethink of European union, Page 2
Delors promises decentralised EC, Page 20
</TEXT>
