FT  25 JUN 92 / International Company News: Daimler confident of rise in
year's sales and profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TURNOVER at Daimler-Benz, the German engineering, aerospace and electronics
group, is likely to be around the 'magic DM100bn mark' this year, up from
DM95bn (Dollars 60.1bn) last year, the company's chief executive reiterated
yesterday.
At the company's annual meeting in Berlin, Mr Edzard Reuter said that
profits were also likely to be ahead of last year's result, but gave no
other details.
This confirms Mr Reuter's optimism as signalled last month when Daimler
reported a 14 per cent increase in first-quarter net profits (to DM480m) and
turnover up 16 per cent to DM22bn.
He stressed that the group's aim was to continue increasing the dividend in
line with growth in profits. It lifted the dividend last year, from DM12 to
DM13 a share, for the first time in six years, following an 8 per cent rise
in net profits to DM1.9bn for the year.
He outlined a number of general risks facing the company in the remaining
months of the year,
but he said Daimler faced the future with 'quiet and confident optimism'.
At Mercedes-Benz, Daimler's vehicle subsidiary, turnover is expected to rise
4.5 per cent to DM70bn this year.
On the passenger vehicle side, he said the new S-Class luxury car model was
proving extraordinarily successful. However, general weakness in world
markets meant that in total unit sales of cars were not as good as had been
hoped at the beginning of the year.
