<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Tarmac begins disposal programme with US
sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TARMAC, has announced the sale for Dollars 42.5m (Pounds 22.9m) of its
Californian contracting and aggregate operations, making it the latest
British construction group to begin a disposal programme to reduce heavy
borrowings.
Mr Neville Simms, recently appointed chief executive, wants to raise between
Pounds 200m and Pounds 250m from sales of non-core businesses.
Earlier this week Costain, another large British construction group,
announced plans to float off part of its profitable Australian coal mining
subsidiary in a further move to reduce borrowings.
Wimpey, the construction and engineering group which is Britain's second
biggest house builder, has raised more than Pounds 300m during the past 12
months from disposals. Taylor Woodrow, another large contractor, has
announced a similar programme to dispose of non-core and underperforming
assets to reduce debts.
At the end of last year Tarmac had net borrowings of Pounds 456.9m and
gearing of 51 per cent. Mr Simms has said that he wanted to reduce gearing
to 25 per cent, mainly through disposals. It is hoped that more than Pounds
100m will be raised from a first phase of sales, to include the Californian
construction business and the British oil refining interests at Ellesmere
Port and Dundee.
A second phase of disposals will include Econowaste, the UK waste disposal
business, which went on the market last week, and which Tarmac expects to
fetch between Pounds 80m and Pounds 100m.
Granite Construction of the US has bought the Californian businesses. The
businesses were acquired by Tarmac in 1986 for about Dollars 20m.
Tarmac, which is Britain's biggest house builder, also has housebuilding
operations in Washington state and Maryland, which are being retained.
</TEXT>
