<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tories to break financial silence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONSERVATIVE party is to take a first step towards increasing the amount
of information published on its finances.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand Deloitte, the accountancy firm, is to be consulted on the
feasibility of publishing a similar amount of information as in companies'
annual reports. That could include, for the first time, detailed figures on
debts.
With the government determined to fulfil its pledge to reduce Whitehall
secrecy, Mr Tim Smith, the Tory vice-chairman with responsibility for party
finances, hopes he may be able to make the changes before 1992-93 accounts
are published next summer.
However, he has ruled out publishing a breakdown of donations. In spite of
occasional controversy surrounding gifts - such as from companies within the
collapsed Polly Peck empire of Mr Asil Nadir - the party argues that donors
have a right to confidentiality.
At present, the Conservative party only publishes a limited set of annual
accounts, audited by Coopers &amp; Lybrand. These show income and expenditure
but not full figures on assets and liabilities.
A move to greater accountability would follow pressure for more openness
from the 'Charter' Group of Conservative activists who want greater
democracy and accountability within the party.
Sir Norman Fowler was appointed Conservative party chairman last month with
a brief to shake-up party organisation. Senior Tories recognise that
Conservative Central Office needs to restore confidence among constituency
associations that finances are effectively and efficiently used at head
office.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand's conclusions are likely to increase the pressure on Sir
Norman to publish more financial information.
</TEXT>
