<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 92 / NUM overtaken in size by Equity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ONCE mighty National Union of Mineworkers was last year overtaken in
size by Equity, the actors' union, as affiliates to the Trades Union
Congress saw their membership decline to the lowest level since 1947.
The NUM's decline to 44,352 at the end of last year compares with 200,000
during the 1984-85 miners' strike and 53,112 in 1990. Membership of Equity
has risen from 32,525 in 1984 to 44,379.
Figures published by the TUC yesterday show that membership of its
affiliates fell last year by 440,000 to 7.76m out of a total workforce of
more than 24m. Mr Norman Willis, TUC general secretary, said: 'Whilst these
figures are disappointing, they say more about the state of the economy than
they do about trade unions.' Unemployment increased by 700,000 last year.
The TUC said it remained the largest national trade union organisation in
western Europe. It added that union density in the UK - the percentage of
the workforce who are members of unions - compared well with other developed
countries.
Of the 72 affiliated unions, 57 recorded a drop in membership last year,
costing the TUC more than Pounds 500,000 in lost affiliation fees.
The three largest unions were among those hardest hit, with the TGWU and GMB
general unions both suffering a 7 per cent decline to 1.13m and 862,000
respectively. The engineering section of the Amalgamated Engineering and
Electrical Union fell 11 per cent to 622,000.
Britain's smallest union - the Sheffield Wool Shear Workers Union - lost one
member, down from 17 to 16.
Gainers included the Nalgo public service union, up from 744,000 to 759,000
and the CPSA Civil Service union, up 1,889 to 124,566.
The latest membership figures mean the TUC's general council will be reduced
by six to 50 members. The TGWU, GMB, AEEU and MSF general technical union -
whose recorded membership fell from 653,000 to 604,000 - will all lose one
seat, as will the UCW communication workers' union.
</TEXT>
