<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / International Company News: SEC plans rules on proxy battles
and executive pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEW rules making it easier for shareholders in US companies to challenge
management during proxy battles and forcing corporations to disclose more
information about executive pay, were proposed by the Securities and
Exchange Commission yesterday.
The proposals, unanimously approved by the SEC's four commissioners at a
meeting in Washington, are part of a campaign by the US watchdog to give
shareholders more say in the management of companies.
The new rules will not come into effect, however, until the SEC has received
comments from the public and corporations on its proposals.
On the proxy issue, the SEC's plan is to simplify the disclosure
requirements imposed on shareholders when they discuss in writing how they
might vote in an annual meeting. At present, a shareholder needs prior
approval from the SEC when communicating in writing with more than 10 other
shareholders.
Oral discussions between shareholders would be exempt from any type of
filing. The SEC also proposed that big shareholders should be allowed to
include a criticism of a company's performance in their proxy statements.
In the past, US corporations have been against the easing of proxy rules,
arguing that it would allow big institutions to organise opposition to
management in secret. The SEC first proposed altering its proxy rules in
June 1991, but was forced to tone down the substance of some of the changes
after receiving more than 900 comment letters, many of them hostile to the
proposals.
Mr Richard Breeden, the Commission's chairman, said yesterday that he would
like to see the changes take effect in time for the 1993 proxy season.
Under the new rules on executive pay, companies would be required to provide
shareholders with clear information on what executives are earning, laid out
in chart form rather than in pages of dense text.
Management would also be forced to show how pay relates to company
performance.
The United Shareholders Association, a Washington-based pressure group,
welcomed the new rules.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
